{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Revise calculation of student loan repayments for overseas graduates",
        "additional_details": "Repayments are calculated as 9% gross income over a threshold.\r\n\r\nDifferent tax systems mean that graduates living abroad can face higher monthly repayments relative to their take-home pay than their UK counterparts. \r\n\r\nFor example, a UK resident with a Plan 1 loan earning \u00a340,000 p.a. would pay \u00a3639 tax/NI and \u00a3104 to student finance, taking home \u00a32589 per month. \r\n\r\nFor the same salary, a graduate in Denmark would pay \u00a31095 in tax, take home \u00a32236, and still have to pay \u00a3104 to student finance.",
        "background": "Calculate the monthly repayment amount for overseas graduates according to post-tax rather than pre-tax income.\r\n(I.e. scale monthly repayments to match those of UK residents with the same take-home pay.)\r\nThis would prevent the effective burden of repayment from being higher in high tax countries.",
